# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cape-horn
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cape-horn/35th-parallel-south] The **31st parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 31 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:cape-horn/35th-parallel-south] It crosses the Atlantic Ocean, Africa, the Indian Ocean, Australasia, the Pacific Ocean and South America.
[src:cape-horn/35th-parallel-south] At this latitude the sun is visible for 14 hours, 13 minutes during the December solstice and 10 hours, 4 minutes during the June solstice.
[src:cape-horn/35th-parallel-south] The **32nd parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 32 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:cape-horn/35th-parallel-south] At this latitude the sun is visible for 14 hours, 19 minutes during the December solstice and 9 hours, 58 minutes during the June solstice.
[src:cape-horn/35th-parallel-south] The **33rd parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 33 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:cape-horn/35th-parallel-south] The **34th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 34 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:cape-horn/35th-parallel-south] At this latitude the sun is visible for 14 hours, 28 minutes during the December solstice and 9 hours, 50 minutes during the June solstice.
[src:cape-horn/35th-parallel-south] South of this latitude, the Crux constellation is circumpolar (never sets below the horizon).
[src:cape-horn/35th-parallel-south] On 21 June, the maximum altitude of the sun is 32.17 degrees, while it's 79.83 degrees on 21 December.
[src:cape-horn/35th-parallel-south] The **35th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 35 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:cape-horn/35th-parallel-south] It crosses the Atlantic Ocean, the Indian Ocean, Australasia, the Pacific Ocean and South America.
[src:cape-horn/35th-parallel-south] At this latitude the sun is visible for 14 hours, 31 minutes during the December solstice and 9 hours, 48 minutes during the June solstice.
[src:cape-horn/35th-parallel-south] This parallel is sometimes used to define the southern boundary of the subtropics.
[src:cape-horn/47th-parallel-south] The **46th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 46 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:cape-horn/47th-parallel-south] At this latitude the sun is visible for 15 hours, 45 minutes during the December solstice and 8 hours, 38 minutes during the June solstice.
[src:cape-horn/47th-parallel-south] This holds true regardless of longitude.
[src:cape-horn/47th-parallel-south] The largest city south of the 46th parallel is Punta Arenas.
[src:cape-horn/47th-parallel-south] The **47th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 47 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:cape-horn/47th-parallel-south] At this latitude, the sun is visible for 15 hours and 54 minutes during the December solstice and 8 hours and 30 minutes during the June solstice.
[src:cape-horn/47th-parallel-south] The **48th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 48 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:cape-horn/47th-parallel-south] It crosses the Atlantic Ocean, the Indian Ocean, the Pacific Ocean and South America.
[src:cape-horn/47th-parallel-south] At this latitude the sun is visible for 16 hours, 3 minutes during the December solstice and 8 hours, 22 minutes during the June solstice.
[src:cape-horn/47th-parallel-south] If the latitude in the southern hemisphere is 48º50' or smaller, it is possible to view both astronomical dawn and dusk every day of the month of January.
[src:cape-horn/47th-parallel-south] At the latitude of 48°33′38.58804” South, which is about 62.3 km (38.7 mi) south of this parallel, is the parallel where twilight/nighttime boundary on the December Solstice.
[src:cape-horn/47th-parallel-south] The **49th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 49 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:cape-horn/47th-parallel-south] At this latitude the sun is visible for 16 hours, 13 minutes during the December solstice and 8 hours, 14 minutes during the June solstice.
[src:cape-horn/47th-parallel-south] This latitude also roughly corresponds to the minimum latitude in which astronomical twilight can last all night near the summer solstice.
[src:cape-horn/47th-parallel-south] All-night astronomical twilight lasts about from December 11 to January 1 of the following year.
[src:cape-horn/47th-parallel-south] At midnight on the summer solstice, the altitude of the sun is about −17.56°.
[src:cape-horn/47th-parallel-south] The **50th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 50 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:cape-horn/47th-parallel-south] At this latitude the sun is visible for 16 hours, 23 minutes during the December solstice and 8 hours, 4 minutes during the June solstice.
[src:cape-horn/47th-parallel-south] On December 21, the sun is at 63.44 degrees in the sky and on June 21, the sun is at 16.56 degrees in the sky.
[src:cape-horn/47th-parallel-south] During the summer solstice, nighttime does not get beyond astronomical twilight, a condition which lasts throughout the month of December.
[src:cape-horn/47th-parallel-south] It is possible to view both astronomical dawn and dusk every day of the month of November.
[src:cape-horn/47th-parallel-south] The maximum altitude of the Sun is > 25.00º in April and > 18.00º in May.
[src:cape-horn/47th-parallel-south] The 50th parallel is the northerly boundary of the Dependencies of the Falkland Islands, the southerly boundary being the 60th parallel south.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] The **56th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 56 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] It crosses Europe, Asia, the Pacific Ocean, North America, and the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] At this latitude the sun is visible for 17 hours, 37 minutes during the summer solstice and 6 hours, 57 minutes during the winter solstice.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] The **57th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 57 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] At this latitude the sun is visible for 17 hours, 53 minutes during the summer solstice and 6 hours, 43 minutes during the winter solstice.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] On June 21, the sun is at 56.44 degrees in the sky and on December 21, the sun is at 9.56 degrees in the sky.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] During the summer solstice, nighttime does not get beyond nautical twilight, a condition which lasts throughout the month of June.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] It is possible to view both astronomical dawn and dusk every day of the month of April.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] The maximum altitude of the Sun is > 18.00º in October and > 11.00º in November.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] The only capital city on the 57th parallel north is Riga.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] The **58th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 58 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] At this latitude the Sun is visible for 18 hours, 11 minutes during the summer solstice and 6 hours, 27 minutes during the winter solstice.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] In general, this parallel sees significant differences in temperature and precipitation with proximity to warm ocean currents.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] The moderation from the Gulf Stream ensures a moderate oceanic climate in much of Western Europe and on the immediate coastline of Alaska, whereas moving inland on continental masses, subarctic climates predominate as the dark winters dominate the temperature cycle.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] In the transitional area centred on the Baltic Sea this latitude sees a humid continental climate with warm summers and snowy winters somewhat below freezing.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] Where cold ocean currents dominate such as near Hudson Bay the climate is polar, rendering in severe winter conditions and very subdued summers.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] This type of climate is seen in the surroundings of Inukjuak in Quebec, Canada, where the sea ice eliminates winter moderation, but the thawing of the cold water renders in very cool summers as well.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] In more continental cold areas such as these winters commonly go below −30 °C or −22 °F even during the day.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] Further west in inland areas winters are often as severe, but summers average above 22 °C or 71.6 °F, similar to the Baltic region where climates are much gentler.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] The **59th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 59 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] At this latitude the Sun is visible for 18 hours, 30 minutes during the summer solstice and 6 hours, 11 minutes during the winter solstice.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] If latitude in northern hemisphere is 59°45′ or smaller, every day in August can view both nautical dawn and nautical dusk.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] The **60th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 60 degrees north of Earth's equator.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] In Canada, the 60th parallel forms the southern mainland boundary of the northern territories of Yukon, Northwest Territories, and Nunavut with the western provinces of British Columbia, Alberta, Saskatchewan, and Manitoba.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] Accordingly, "north of 60" is an expression often used for the territories.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] The 60th Parallel Territorial Park is on Mackenzie Highway between Alberta and Northwest Territories and it has a visitor centre there in the homeland of the Yellowknives Dene First Nation and the North Slave Métis Alliance.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] Between 1776 and 1950, the 60th parallel formed the southern limit of the Royal Greenland Trade Department's exclusive monopoly on trade near the Dano-Norwegian and later Danish colonies of Greenland (1776–1782) and South Greenland (1782–1950).
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] Although it lies approximately twice as far away from the Equator as from the North Pole, the 60th parallel is half as long as the Equator line, due to the cosine of 60 degrees being 0.5.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] This is where the Earth bulges halfway as much as on the Equator.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] At this latitude, the Sun is visible for 18 hours, 52 minutes during the June solstice and 5 hours, 52 minutes during the December solstice.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] The maximum altitude of the Sun is 53.44° on 21 June and 6.56° on 21 December.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] The maximum altitude of the Sun is > 15.00º in October and > 8.00º in November.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] The lowest latitude where white nights can be observed is approximately on this parallel.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] It is possible to view both astronomical dawn and dusk every day between August 22 and April 21.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-north] Malachy Tallack wrote a book, *Sixty Degrees North: Around the World in Search of Home*, about his travels along the general line of the parallel, starting and finishing at Shetland.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] The following are **circles of latitude between the 55th parallel south and the South Pole**.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] The 55th parallel south, crossing the southernmost point of Chile, is the last line of latitude moving southward to touch any part of any continent other than Antarctica, other than minor outlying islands.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] The **56th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 56 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] No land lies on the parallel — it crosses nothing but ocean.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] At this latitude the sun is visible for 17 hours, 37 minutes during the December solstice and 6 hours, 57 minutes during the June solstice.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] The **57th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 57 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] At this latitude the sun is visible for 17 hours, 53 minutes during the December solstice and 6 hours, 43 minutes during the June solstice.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] On December 21, the sun is at 56.44 degrees in the sky and on June 21, the sun is at 9.56 degrees in the sky.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] During the summer solstice, nighttime does not get beyond nautical twilight, a condition which lasts throughout the month of December.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] It is possible to view both astronomical dawn and dusk every day of the month of October.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] The maximum altitude of the Sun is > 18.00º in April and > 11.00º in May.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] The **58th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 58 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] At this latitude the sun is visible for 18 hours, 11 minutes during the December solstice and 6 hours, 27 minutes during the June solstice.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] The **59th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 59 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] The only landmass on this parallel is Bristol Island.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] At this latitude the sun is visible for 18 hours, 30 minutes during the December solstice and 6 hours, 10 minutes during the June solstice.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] The **60th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 60 degrees south of Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] No land lies on the parallel—it crosses nothing but ocean.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] The parallel marks the northern limit of the Southern Ocean (though some organisations and countries, notably Australia, have other definitions) and of the Antarctic Treaty System.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] It also marks the southern boundary of the South Pacific Nuclear-Weapon-Free Zone and the Latin American Nuclear-Weapon-Free Zone.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] At this latitude the sun is visible for 18 hours, 52 minutes during the December solstice and 5 hours, 52 minutes during the June solstice.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] On December 21, the sun is at 53.44 degrees up in the sky and 6.56 degrees on June 21.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] The sun's altitude is exactly 30 degrees at either equinox.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] The latitudes south of this parallel are often referred to as the Screaming 60s due to the prevailing high-speed, westerly winds which can generate large waves in excess of 15 m (50 ft) and peak wind speeds over 145 km/h (90 mph).
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] The maximum altitude of the Sun is > 15.00º in April and > 8.00º in May.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] It is possible to view both astronomical dawn and dusk every day between February 17 and October 24.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] The **61st parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 61 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] No land lies on the parallel—it crosses nothing but the Southern Ocean.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] At this latitude the sun is visible for 19 hours, 16 minutes during the December solstice and 5 hours, 32 minutes during the June solstice.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] On the December solstice, the sun's altitude is 52.44 degrees and on the June solstice, it is 5.56 degrees.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] The lowest latitude where civil twilight can last all night lies approximately on this parallel.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] The **62nd parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 62 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] It crosses the Southern Ocean and Antarctica.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] At this latitude the sun is visible for 19 hours, 45 minutes during the December solstice and 5 hours, 9 minutes during the June solstice.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] The **63rd parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 63 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] At this latitude the sun is visible for 20 hours, 19 minutes during the December solstice and 4 hours, 42 minutes during the June solstice.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] If the latitude in the southern hemisphere is 63º26' or smaller, it is possible to view both astronomical dawn and dusk every day of the month of March.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] The **64th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 64 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] It crosses the Southern Ocean and the Antarctic mainland, the latter as the most northern latitude.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] At this latitude the sun is visible for 21 hours, 1 minute during the December solstice and 4 hours, 12 minutes during the June solstice.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] The **65th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 65 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] At this latitude the sun is visible for 22 hours, 2 minutes during the December solstice and 3 hours, 35 minutes during the June solstice.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] The **66th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 66 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane, about 61 km north of the Antarctic Circle.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] This latitude also roughly corresponds to the minimum latitude in which midnight sun can last all night near the summer solstice.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] At this latitude the sun rises on December 13 and does not set again until December 30.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] The **67th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 67 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane, about 50 km south of the Antarctic Circle.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] At this latitude the sun is visible for 24 hours, 0 minutes during the December solstice (Summer solstice) and 1 hour, 29 minutes during the June solstice (Winter solstice).
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] If the latitude in the southern hemisphere is 67°45′ or smaller, every day of the month of September can view both astronomical dawn and astronomical dusk.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] The **68th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 68 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane, in the Antarctic.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] At this latitude, the sun is visible for 24 hours, 0 minutes during the December Solstice, and civil twilight during the June Solstice.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] The **69th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 69 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane, in the Antarctic.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] The **70th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 70 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane in the Antarctic.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] The parallel passes through the Southern Ocean and Antarctica.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] The **71st parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 71 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane in the Antarctic.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] The **72nd parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 72 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane in the Antarctic.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] This is the parallel where twilight/nighttime boundary on the equinoxes.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] This is also the lowest parallel that golden hour occurs even at midnight sun, because the Sun is less than 6°00'00" above the horizon.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] Midnight sun without golden hour occurs at latitudes greater than 72°33'38.58804", i.e., about 666.8 km (414.3 mi) south of the Antarctic Circle in the case of the **December Solstice**.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] The **73rd parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 73 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane in the Antarctic.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] The **74th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 74 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane in the Antarctic.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] The **75th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 75 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane in the Antarctic.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p01] It passes through the Southern Ocean and Antarctica.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p02] The **76th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 76 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane in the Antarctic.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p02] The **77th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 77 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane in the Antarctic.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p02] The **78th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 78 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane in the Antarctic.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p02] The **79th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 79 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane in the Antarctic.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p02] The parallel passes only through Antarctica and Antarctic ice shelves.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p02] The **80th parallel south** is a circle of latitude that is 80 degrees south of the Earth's equatorial plane, and 10 degrees (690 miles/1100 kilometers) north of the United States Amundsen–Scott South Pole Station.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p02] Regions south of this latitude are excluded from UTM zones.
[src:cape-horn/56th-parallel-south-p02] This line of latitude passes only through Antarctica and Antarctic ice shelves.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] Commander **Alwyn Thomas Lavender Covey-Crump** (19 February 1907 – 19 May 1991) was a British officer of the Royal Navy.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] An assistant to the Chief of Naval Information, he was responsible in the mid-1950s for compiling a record of Jack-speak (naval slang) and other historical marine linguistic details.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] The first edition appeared on 17 May 1955.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] The compilation, now continually updated, has led to the term *Covey-Crump* itself entering into Royal Navy slang.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] Covey-Crump served in various ships between 1927 and 1945, including HMS *Vindictive*, HMS *Enterprise*, HMS *Duncan*, HMS *Faulkner*, HMS *Boscawen*, HMS *Ceylon* and HMS *Liverpool*.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] He was the second son of Reverend Canon Walter William Covey-Crump, and was married with one son.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] Covey-Crump was born on 19 February 1907 in Stopsley, Bedfordshire.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] He was the second son of Reverend Canon Walter William Covey-Crump; his mother was Hilda Sophia (née Porter).
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] His parents married on 11 June 1903 at Haddenham, when his father was by then using the name Covey as a given name.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] The family was using the double-barrelled name, Covey-Crump, by 1911.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] Covey-Crump had two brothers: musician Lewis Charles Leslie, and Leo William Rolf, who served in the Royal Naval Volunteer Reserve in World War II.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] In 1938, Covey-Crump married Joyce Blackstone at St James, Picadilly, London. the daughter of T.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] Blackstone, former Deputy Inspector General of Police and Police Commissioner in Southern India.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] The 1939 England and Wales Register finds him at Flat 5, Nirvana Mansions, Portsmouth.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] The 1957 Electoral Register finds Covey-Crump and his wife Joyce living at 19 Trenham Drive, Warlingham, Surrey.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] He died aged 84 on 19 May 1991 at St Albans, and was buried on 24 May.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] On 1 September 1925, aged 18, Covey-Crump was appointed acting paymaster sub-lieutenant or paymaster midshipman.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] In December 1927 he passed his accountant officers' examination, class 2, while serving on HMS *Vindictive*.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] On 1 June 1929 he was promoted to paymaster lieutenant.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] In 1931 he was deployed to HMS *Enterprise*.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] From 14 September 1934 he was deployed to HMS *Vernon*, a shore establishment in Portsmouth.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] He was appointed to HMS *Duncan* from 10 September 1935.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] From 28 September 1936 he was deployed as secretary to Captain Victor Danckwerts of HMS *Faulkner*, leader of the 6th Destroyer Flotilla.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] From 1 June 1937 he was paymaster lieutenant-commander.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] On 16 August 1938 he was sent to HMS *Victory* shore establishment for an accountant officers' technical course.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] On 2 January 1939 he was again deployed to HMS *Victory* for Tactical School.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] On 11 August 1939, Covey-Crump was appointed to the shore establishment *HMS Boscawen*.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] In that year, he was assistant to the Chief of Naval Information.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] He was promoted to commander on 1 June 1943.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] In 1944, he was serving on the cruiser HMS *Ceylon*.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] In 1946, Covey-Crump was serving at HMS *St George* shore training establishment, finishing in January 1948.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] In February 1948, he was appointed to HMS *St Vincent*, a shore training establishment.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] He was appointed to HMS *Liverpool* from 15 March 1948 until at least August 1950.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] On 22 January 1950, while Covey-Crump was serving in the Mediterranean under Vice Admiral Louis Mountbatten on HMS *Liverpool*, King Farouk visited the ship, and was presented with a special matchbox when lighting his cigar.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] "From the ship's *Father Christmas* one of the officers, Commander A.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] Covey-Crump, had received the present of six boxes of matches.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] The specially-printed label bears the legend *Commander Covey's Crumptious Matches* beneath a horseshoe".
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] Farouk was a collector and belonged to the British Matchbox Labels Society (BMLS); the gift was described as a "great rarity".
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] The president of the BMLS also owned one of the six labels.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] In 1955, Covey-Crump's compilation of Jack-speak was published within the Navy.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] He was appointed registrar at the Royal Naval Barracks, Devonport the same year.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] Covey-Crump privately published, within the Royal Navy, his first-edition typescript of *Alphabetical Glossary of Naval Terms and Abbreviations* on 17 May 1955.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] It contains "a collection of Naval slang, abbreviations, legends and historical tit-bits", and a list of Naval nicknames.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] The National Archives website has an online transcription of it, commenting that it "provides a valuable resource for researchers looking for answers to many historical questions about the Royal Navy".
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] The historical reenactment company HMS Richmond suggests that the collection of Jack-speak in this compilation is centred on the period around 1775.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] It is "mainly aimed at those with a background in the senior service", and was "the first official collection of naval slang".
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] The compilation itself became known in the Royal Navy as *Covey-Crump* and the phrase thus entered the list of naval slang.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] One example from the compilation is: "Blazer: The name for this coloured coat comes from HMS *Blazer*, whose Captain (Captain J.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] Washington) in 1845 had his boat's crew dressed in blue and white-striped jackets.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] This was, of course, before the days of authorised uniform for Naval ratings".
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] Jackspeak continues to evolve: Covey-Crump's 1955 edition marks a moment in time, and there was an updated edition in 1967.
[src:cape-horn/a-t-l-covey-crump] Surgeon Captain Rick Jolly, who as a surgeon commander with the Commando Logistic Regiment commanded the field hospital at Ajax Bay during the Falklands War produced his own dictionary of "Jackspeak" in aid of the South Atlantic Medal Association, in 2000.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] The second-eldest of Marianne and Laurence Sunderland's eight children, Sunderland grew up sailing with her family.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] Her brother, Zac Sunderland, was the first person under the age of 18 to complete a circumnavigation.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] She and her siblings have been homeschooled.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] A lifelong sailor, Sunderland said she had been preparing for her journey since age 13.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] Her father Laurence Sunderland said he understood her determination when "It was a particularly rough day and her boat was rocking from gunnel to gunnel. ...
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] I knew she was freezing cold, tired and hungry, and we'd been at it for, you know, 20 hours at that stage.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] Sunderland's yacht *Wild Eyes* was a 40-foot (12.19 m) sloop built in 2001 by A.S.A.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] Designed by Jutson Yacht, it was purported to be made specifically for sailing single-handed through the Southern Ocean, but post-rescue reporting disputed this.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] Under its earlier name *BTC Velocity* the vessel finished second in the Class 3 (Open 40) category of the Around Alone 2002 race.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] *Wild Eyes* was constructed of fiberglass with Kevlar reinforcement into five watertight compartments with a crash bulkhead and a stern escape hatch.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] It was bought in Rhode Island by the Sunderland family in October 2009 and refitted in Marina Del Rey, California, with an array of electrical, communication and navigation systems.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] Sunderland started her solo circumnavigation from Marina del Rey, California, on January 23, 2010.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] There had not been enough time to do a multi-day test sail in varying conditions, so the team decided to let her depart anyway, and stop in Cabo San Lucas, Mexico, if needed.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] After a few days it became evident that her solar panels and wind turbines were not meeting the energy needs of her boat in the conditions she met, so using the diesel engine was needed more than anticipated.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] There were also electrical problems in her mast wiring, which affected her windspeed indicators.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] Sunderland landed at Cabo San Lucas on February 2, 2010, to take on more fuel and batteries, make repairs and restart her non-stop circumnavigation attempt.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] Sunderland started her second attempt from Cabo San Lucas on February 6, 2010, intending to complete a solo, non-stop, unassisted circumnavigation in ten legs, departing from and returning to Cabo San Lucas.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] On February 19, 2010, at 3:07 PM PST, thirteen days after departing Cabo San Lucas, Sunderland and *Wild Eyes* crossed the equator into the South Pacific at 0°00′N 120°15′W﻿ / ﻿0°N 120.25°W﻿ / 0; -120.25﻿ (Sunderland crosses the equator, February 19, 2010).
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] On February 27, 2010, there was media concern for Sunderland's safety because of the 2010 Chile earthquake.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] On March 21, 2010, while sleeping at approximately 2:00 AM local time, she suffered a knockdown and barely avoided an accidental jibe.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] On March 31, 2010, Sunderland rounded Cape Horn—the southernmost point of South America—making her the youngest solo sailor to do so.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] She experienced rough seas and heavy winds when approaching, but little wind the last day before Cape Horn.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] On April 24, 2010, Sunderland announced that she would stop at Cape Town for repairs to her autopilot system, ending her non-stop attempt.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] However, she planned to continue the circumnavigation.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] Sunderland had two separate autopilot systems and both failed.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] She was able to swap parts between them to keep one going for a time, but a leak made the repair stop necessary.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] She arrived in Cape Town on May 5, 2010.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] Around May 24, 2010, a line got stuck near the top of her mast.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] Sunderland tried to climb the mast but found it too dangerous in the near gale conditions and full darkness, so she sailed throughout that night under reduced sails.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] On the morning of June 10, 2010, Sunderland was sailing in high winds and had suffered multiple knockdowns in a remote area of the Indian Ocean northeast of the Kerguelen Islands, about 2,000 miles (3,200 km) west of Australia.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] Satellite phone contact was lost and about an hour later Sunderland's two manually operated emergency radio beacons were activated.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] A third beacon which triggers automatically if it goes 15 feet (4.6 m) underwater was not activated.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] The nearest known ship was about 400 miles (640 km) away from her electronically reported position.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] The next morning, the Australian Maritime Safety Authority sent a chartered Qantas Airbus A330 passenger jet to the area with 11 trained SES air observers and a FESA officer on board.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] The search plane faced a 4,700 miles (7,600 km) round trip from Perth to Sunderland's boat, a distance near the limit of its range.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] The boat was sighted about 10 minutes after the plane reached its search zone.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] Brief, short-range radio contact was made with Sunderland, who said she had righted the boat and was uninjured.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] Despite earlier fears that her sailing yacht had lost its keel and capsized, the boat was upright but dismasted, its rig dragging in the ocean from the broken mast, making satellite phone reception impossible.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] Sunderland's mother said the pilot of the Australian search plane told her the boat had probably been "rolled by a rogue wave." Her father said his daughter's circumnavigation attempt had come to an end.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] The area where Sunderland's yacht was adrift is rarely visited by merchant ships or other sea traffic.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] The Australian Maritime Safety Authority's Rescue Coordination Centre put together a sea response with three ships traveling to the scene.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] Sunderland was rescued by the French commercial fishing vessel *Ile de la Réunion* late in the afternoon on June 12, 2010.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] Air cover for the rescue was handled from a privately owned Global Express corporate jet, which also relayed communications between her and the fishing vessel before its crew launched a small boat to ferry her from the crippled sailing yacht.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] In a statement the Australian Maritime Safety Authority said "The master of the *Ile De La Réunion* has reported Ms.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] In Thousand Oaks, California, Laurence Sunderland told reporters "She got out of her vessel with the clothes on her back." Aboard the *Ile de la Réunion* Sunderland wrote that "one long wave" had brought about the dismasting of her sail boat *Wild Eyes*, which was abandoned to the ocean.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] The *Ile de la Reunion* took Sunderland to the Kerguelen Islands where she boarded a French patrol boat, the *Osiris*, for an 8-day trip to Reunion Island.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] Australian and French taxpayers bore some of the expenses for Sunderland's rescue and the Australian government confirmed that by law, she or her family cannot be billed for the expenses.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] It has been reported the Qantas plane used to spot her costs A$10,000 an hour to operate.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] The total cost of the international rescue is estimated by media to be up to £116,000 (A$200,000) or A$300,000 depending on source.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] There has been criticism of her team's lack of contribution to rescue costs.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] In France, a law has been proposed that tourists could be required to reimburse the state for rescue costs if they "ventured knowingly and without 'legitimate motive' into risky territory".
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] After her rescue, Sunderland said she hoped to sail around the world again some time in the future.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] Sunderland was the subject of a documentary film produced and directed by her father titled *Wild Eyes: The Abby Sunderland Story*.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] The film was released on September 8, 2011.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] Sunderland released a book about her ordeal on April 12, 2011.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] The book is co-written with Lynn Vincent and is titled *Unsinkable: A Young Woman's Courageous Battle on the High Seas*.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] She has been going on book-signing tours, where it was revealed that she is taking flying lessons, to be able to fly around the world.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] In 2018 an overturned vessel spotted off the coast of Kangaroo Island was identified as *Wild Eyes*.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] News pictures appear to show it as having lost its keel.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] An Australian official said that it will not be salvaged unless it poses a hazard to shipping or comes ashore.
[src:cape-horn/abby-sunderland] In 2018 Sunderland was living in Alabama, is married with three children, with one on the way.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Cape Horn was identified by mariners and first rounded in 1616 by the Dutchmen Willem Schouten and Jacob Le Maire, who named it *Kaap Hoorn* (pronunciationⓘ) after the city of Hoorn in the Netherlands.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] For decades, Cape Horn was a major milestone on the clipper route, by which sailing ships carried trade around the world.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] The waters around Cape Horn are particularly hazardous, owing to strong winds, large waves, strong currents and icebergs.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] The need for boats and ships to round Cape Horn was greatly reduced by the opening of the Panama Canal in August 1914.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Sailing around Cape Horn is still widely regarded as one of the major challenges in yachting.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Thus, a few recreational sailors continue to sail this route, sometimes as part of a circumnavigation of the globe.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Almost all of these choose routes through the channels to the north of the Cape (many take a detour through the islands and anchor to wait for fair weather to visit Horn Island, or sail around it to replicate a rounding of this historic point).
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Several prominent ocean yacht races, notably the Volvo Ocean Race, Velux 5 Oceans Race, and the solo Vendée Globe and Golden Globe Race, sail around the world via the Horn.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Speed records for round-the-world sailing are recognized for following this route.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Cape Horn is located on Hornos Island in the Hermite Islands group, at the southern end of the Tierra del Fuego archipelago.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] It marks the northern edge of the Drake Passage, the strait between South America and Antarctica.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] It is located in Cabo de Hornos National Park, Core of the Cape Horn Biosphere Reserve.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] A short distance from the main station is a memorial, including a large sculpture made by Chilean sculptor José Balcells featuring the silhouette of an albatross, in remembrance of the sailors who died while attempting to "round the Horn".
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] It was erected in 1992 through the initiative of the Chilean Section of the Cape Horn Captains Brotherhood.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Due to severe winds characteristic of the region, the sculpture was blown over in 2014.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] A 2019 research expedition found the world's southernmost tree growing, a Magellan's beech mostly bent to the ground, on a northeast-facing slope at the island's southeast corner.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Cape Horn is the southern limit of the range of the Magellanic penguin.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] The climate in the region is generally cool, owing to the southern latitude.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] There are no weather stations in the group of islands including Cape Horn, but a study in 1882–1883 found an annual rainfall of 1,357 millimetres (53.4 inches), with an average annual temperature of 5.2 °C (41.4 °F).
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Winds were reported to average 30 kilometres per hour (8.3 m/s; 18.6 mph), (5 Bf), with squalls of over 100 kilometres per hour (27.8 m/s; 62.1 mph), (10 Bf) occurring in all seasons.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] There are 278 days of rainfall, (70 days snow) and 2,000 millimetres (79 inches) of annual rainfall.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Cloud coverage is generally extensive, with averages from 5.2 eighths in May and July to 6.4 eighths in December and January.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Wind conditions are generally severe, particularly in winter.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] In summer, the wind at Cape Horn is gale force up to 5 percent of the time, with generally good visibility; however, in winter, gale-force winds occur up to 30 percent of the time, often with poor visibility.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Many stories are told of hazardous journeys "around the Horn", most describing fierce storms.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Being the southernmost point of land outside of Antarctica, the region experiences barely 7 hours of daylight during the June solstice, with Cape Horn itself having 6 hours and 57 minutes.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] The region experiences around 17+1⁄2 hours of daylight during the December solstice, and experiences only nautical twilight from civil dusk to civil dawn.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] White nights occur during the week around the December solstice.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Cape Horn yields a polar climate (*ET*), with abundant precipitation—much of which falls as sleet and snow.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Cape Horn is part of the Commune of Cabo de Hornos, whose capital is Puerto Williams; this in turn is part of Antártica Chilena Province, whose capital is also Puerto Williams.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] The area is part of the Magallanes y la Antártica Chilena Region of Chile.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Puerto Toro, a few miles south of Puerto Williams, is the closest town to the cape.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] There are no regular commercial routes around the Horn, and modern ships carrying cargo are rarely seen.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] However, a number of cruise ships routinely round the Horn when traveling from one ocean to the other.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] These often stop in Ushuaia or Punta Arenas as well as Port Stanley.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Some of the small passenger vessels shuttling between Ushuaia and the Antarctic Peninsula will pass the Horn too, time and weather permitting.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] A number of potential sailing routes may be followed around the tip of South America.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] The Strait of Magellan, between the mainland and Tierra del Fuego, is a major—although narrow—passage, which was in use for trade well before the Horn was discovered.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] The Beagle Channel (named for the ship of Charles Darwin's expedition), between Tierra del Fuego and Isla Navarino, offers a potential, though difficult route.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Other passages may be taken around the Wollaston and Hermite Islands to the north of Cape Horn.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] All of these, however, are notorious for treacherous *williwaw* winds, which can strike a vessel with little or no warning; given the narrowness of these routes, vessels have a significant risk of being driven onto the rocks.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Rounding Cape Horn can be done on a day trip by helicopter or more arduously by charter power boat or sailboat, or by cruise ship.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] The 50th parallel south on both coasts of South America represent a set of benchmark latitudes of a Horn run, and is a region of the ocean that according to Herman Melville, "takes the conceit out of fresh-water sailors, and steeps in a still saltier brine the saltiest".
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] The prevailing winds in latitudes below 40° south can blow from west to east around the world almost uninterrupted by land, giving rise to the "roaring forties" and the even more wild "furious fifties" and "screaming sixties".
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] These winds are hazardous enough that ships traveling east would tend to stay in the northern part of the forties (i.e. not far below 40° south latitude); however, rounding Cape Horn requires ships to press south to 56° south latitude, well into the zone of fiercest winds.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] These winds are exacerbated at the Horn by the funneling effect of the Andes and the Antarctic Peninsula, which channel the winds into the relatively narrow Drake Passage.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] The strong winds of the Southern Ocean give rise to correspondingly large waves; these waves can attain great height as they roll around the Southern Ocean, free of any interruption from land.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] South of the Horn, however, these waves encounter an area of shallow water, which has the effect of making the waves shorter and steeper, greatly increasing the hazard to ships.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] If the strong eastward current through the Drake Passage encounters an opposing westerly wind, this can have the effect of further building up the waves.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] In addition to these "normal" waves, the area west of the Horn is particularly notorious for rogue waves, which can attain heights of up to 30 metres (98 feet).
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] The prevailing winds and currents create particular problems for vessels trying to round the Horn against them, i.e. from east to west.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Ice is a hazard to sailors venturing far below 40° south.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Although the ice limit dips south around the horn, icebergs are a significant hazard for vessels in the area.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] In the South Pacific in February (summer in Southern Hemisphere), icebergs are generally confined to below 50° south; but in August the iceberg hazard can extend north of 40° south.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Even in February, the Horn is well below the latitude of the iceberg limit.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] These hazards have made the Horn notorious as perhaps the most dangerous ship passage in the world; many ships have been wrecked, and many sailors have died attempting to round the Cape.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Two lighthouses are located near or in Cape Horn.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] The one located in the Chilean Navy Station is the more accessible and visited, and is commonly referred to as *the* Cape Horn lighthouse .
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] On Cape Horn proper is a smaller 4-metre (13-foot) fiberglass light tower, with a focal plane of 40 metres (130 feet) and a range of about 21 kilometres (13 miles).
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] A few minor aids to navigation are located farther south, including one in the Diego Ramírez Islands and several in Antarctica.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Despite the opening of the Suez and Panama Canals, the Horn remains part of the fastest sailing route around the world, and so the growth in recreational long-distance sailing has brought about a revival of sailing via the Horn.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Owing to the remoteness of the location and the hazards there, a rounding of Cape Horn is widely considered to be the yachting equivalent of climbing Mount Everest, and so many sailors seek it for its own sake.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Joshua Slocum was the first single-handed yachtsman to successfully pass this way (in 1895) although in the end, extreme weather forced him to use some of the inshore routes between the channels and islands and it is believed he did not actually pass outside the Horn proper.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] If one had to go by strict definitions, the first small boat to sail around outside Cape Horn was the Irish 42-foot (13-metre) yacht *Saoirse*, sailed by Conor O'Brien with three friends, who rounded it during a circumnavigation of the world between 1923 and 1925.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] In 1934, the Norwegian Al Hansen was the first to round Cape Horn single-handed from east to west—the "wrong way"—in his boat *Mary Jane*, but was subsequently wrecked on the coast of Chile.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] On March 31, 2010, 16-year-old Abby Sunderland became the youngest person to single-handedly sail around Cape Horn in her attempt to circumnavigate the globe.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] In 1987 The British Cape Horn Expedition, headed by Nigel H.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Seymour, rounded Cape Horn in the world's first ever 'sailing kayaks', called 'Kaymaran'; two seagoing kayaks which could link together with two sails mountable in any of the four sailing positions between the two kayaks.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Today, there are several major yacht races held regularly along the old clipper route via Cape Horn.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] The first of these was the *Sunday Times Golden Globe Race*, which was a single-handed race; this inspired the present-day *Around Alone* race, which circumnavigates with stops, and the *Vendée Globe*, which is non-stop.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Both of these are single-handed races, and are held every four years.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] The *Volvo Ocean Race* is a crewed race with stops which sails the clipper route every four years.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Its origins lie in the *Whitbread Round the World Race* first competed in 1973–74.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] The Jules Verne Trophy is a prize for the fastest circumnavigation of the world by any type of yacht, with no restrictions on the size of the crew (no assistance, non-stop).
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Finally, the *Global Challenge* race goes around the world the "wrong way", from east to west, which involves rounding Cape Horn against the prevailing winds and currents.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] The Horn remains a major hazard for recreational sailors, however.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] A classic case is that of Miles and Beryl Smeeton, who attempted to round the Horn in their yacht *Tzu Hang*.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Hit by a rogue wave when approaching the Horn, the boat pitchpoled (i.e. somersaulted end-over-end).
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] They survived, and were able to make repairs in Talcahuano, Chile, and later attempted the passage again, only to be rolled over and dismasted for a second time by another rogue wave, which again they miraculously survived.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] It appears as *Mar de Hoces* (Sea of Hoces) in most Spanish-language maps.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] In English charts however it is named the Drake Passage.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] In September 1578, Sir Francis Drake, in the course of his circumnavigation of the world, passed through the Strait of Magellan into the Pacific Ocean.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Before he could continue his voyage north his ships encountered a storm, and were blown well to the south of Tierra del Fuego.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] The expanse of open water they encountered led Drake to guess that far from being another continent, as previously believed, Tierra del Fuego was an island with open sea to its south.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] This discovery went unused for some time, as ships continued to use the known passage through the Strait of Magellan.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] By the early 17th century the Dutch East India Company was given a monopoly on all Dutch trade via the Straits of Magellan and the Cape of Good Hope, the only known sea routes at the time to the Far East.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] To search for an alternate route and one to the unknown *Terra Australis*, Isaac Le Maire, a wealthy Amsterdam merchant and Willem Schouten, a ship's master of Hoorn, contributed in equal shares to the enterprise, with additional financial support from merchants of Hoorn.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Jacob Le Maire, Isaac's son, went on the journey as "chiefe Marchant and principall factor," in charge of trading aspects of the endeavour.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] The two ships that departed Holland at the beginning of June 1615 were the *Eendracht* of 360 tons with Schouten and Le Maire aboard, and the *Hoorn* of 110 tons, of which Schouten's brother Johan was master.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] At the time it was discovered, the Horn was believed to be the southernmost point of Tierra del Fuego; the unpredictable violence of weather and sea conditions in the Drake Passage made exploration difficult, and it was only in 1624 that the Horn was discovered to be an island.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] It is a telling testament to the difficulty of conditions there that Antarctica, only 650 kilometres (400 miles) away across the Drake Passage, was discovered only as recently as 1820, despite the passage having been used as a major shipping route for 200 years.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] From the 18th to the early 20th centuries, Cape Horn was a part of the clipper routes which carried much of the world's trade.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Sailing ships sailed round the Horn carrying wool, grain, and gold from Australia back to Europe; these included the windjammers in the heyday of the Great Grain Race of the 1930s.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Much trade was carried around the Horn between Europe and the Far East; and trade and passenger ships travelled between the coasts of the United States via the Horn.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] The Horn exacted a heavy toll from shipping, however, owing to the extremely hazardous combination of conditions there.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] The only facilities in the vicinity able to service or supply a ship, or provide medical care, were in the Falkland Islands.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] The businesses there were so notorious for price-gouging that damaged ships were sometimes abandoned at Port Stanley.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] None of them were lost travelling around the Horn, but some, like the mighty *Preußen*, were victims of collisions in the busy English Channel.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Traditionally, a sailor who had rounded the Horn was entitled to wear a gold loop earring—in the left ear, the one which had faced the Horn in a typical eastbound passage—and to dine with one foot on the table; a sailor who had also rounded the Cape of Good Hope could place both feet on the table.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] One particular historic attempt to round the Horn, that of HMS *Bounty* in 1788, has been immortalized in history due to the subsequent Mutiny on the Bounty.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] This abortive Horn voyage has been portrayed (with varying historical accuracy) in three major motion pictures about Captain William Bligh's mission to transport breadfruit plants from Tahiti to Jamaica.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] The Bounty made only 85 miles of headway in 31 days of east-to-west sailing, before giving up by reversing course and going around Africa.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] The transcontinental railroads in North America, as well as the Panama Canal that opened in 1914 in Central America, led to the gradual decrease in use of the Horn for trade.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] As steamships replaced sailing ships, Flying P-Liner *Pamir* became the last commercial sailing ship to round Cape Horn laden with cargo, carrying grain from Port Victoria, Australia, to Falmouth, England, in 1949.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Cape Horn has been an icon of sailing culture for centuries; it has featured in sea shanties and in many books about sailing.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] After nine more days of headwinds and unabated storms, Dana reported that his ship, the "Pilgrim" finally cleared the turbulent waters of Cape Horn and turned northwards.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Alan Villiers, a modern-day expert in traditional sailing ships, wrote many books about traditional sailing, including *By way of Cape Horn*.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] More recent sailors have taken on the Horn singly, such as Vito Dumas, who wrote *Alone Through The Roaring Forties* based on his round-the-world voyage; or with small crews.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Bernard Moitessier made two significant voyages round the Horn; once with his wife Françoise, described in *Cape Horn: The Logical Route*, and once single-handed.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] His book *The Long Way* tells the story of this latter voyage, and of a peaceful night-time passage of the Horn: "The little cloud underneath the moon has moved to the right.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] I look... there it is, so close, less than 10 miles (16 km) away and right under the moon.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] And nothing remains but the sky and the moon playing with the Horn.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] A memorial presented in Robert FitzRoy's bicentenary (2005) commemorates his landing on Cape Horn on 19 April 1830.
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Canadian singer-songwriter Gordon Lightfoot wrote a song entitled "Ghosts of Cape Horn".
[src:cape-horn/cape-horn] Critchlow directed and produced the documentary film "Ghosts of Cape Horn", with the participation and archaeological consulting of famous underwater archaeologist Peter Throckmorton.
